matt-SmartBear
2017-05-10 04:24:10

Welcome @channel. I want to get some feedback on an idea. We’ve always had a CfP for CukeUp in the past, but because that part of the conference is only one day this year (and single track) we’ve filled the programme without a CfP. There’s obviously the CukeSpace which will allow lots of people to get to run a session.

I’m wondering whether it would be nice for some people (perhaps those who might not feel confident about going to an open space) to have a way to submit ideas about sessions they could run and get feedback from the community before the event. We could even give tickets (and / or travel / accommodation) to people who propose sessions that are popular.

What do you think?

artismarti
2017-05-10 05:35:30

@matt-SmartBear Do you mean propose a talk for the open space at a prior event & get feedback on it?

matt-SmartBear
2017-05-10 05:54:34

@artismarti I was more thinking of some kind of lightweight submissions system (e.g. Trello, or this Slack group maybe) where people could propose / discuss ideas for sessions beforehand.

MoM for the Cucumber-Ruby 3.0.0 session: Must have:

  • no lost events (#1041)
  • summary printout and exit code with --retry (#1044)
  • TC count event optional
  • s/ing/ed/g in event names

Could have:

  • Extract steps mechanims as gem
  • Test suite works on Windows

Out of scope:

  • Deprecate custom formatter that use legacy API
  • Deprecate remove wire protocol
  • PR to History script/bot

Karnam
2017-11-13 12:35:39

Hi , This is Karnam and new to cucumber test framework , I am developing a RESTful webservices using spring boot which runs on tomcat server, And I am looking forward to use cucumber test framework as BDD. No idea when(as part of jenkins maven build or after deployment) to execute the cucumber test scenarios. Thanks in advance .

Ray
2017-11-14 01:48:54

*Thread Reply:* I would think to create your Cucumber BDD features from your code deployed to the Tomcat server. But the test code the runs your test can be run on the any level. This is because I think Cucumber is best at describing the behaviour and therefore testing it from the end user perspective. I would expect the scenarios and steps to be user action focused. But the test code (step definitions) can target the application code's units, integrations, user interface without issue. My humble opinion....

kimb
2017-12-05 08:14:45

Hi all, I'd like to submit a proposal for a 15 minute task for Cukenfest. Looking for what might be interesting to people here. I'm quite new to BDD/Cucumber testing but here what I've been doing:

  1. Set up a test Project using SpecFlow (C#) to target a running web server for API testing (no UI)
  2. Configured publishing results to TestRails using their public API
  3. Set up logging to keep track of all requests/responses during a test run
  4. Made the tests run in parallel
  5. (WIP) Got the tests running as part of the VSTS CI build
  6. Publishing features to CucumberPro for sharing
  7. Usage of tags to label tests for "KnownIssues", "InDevelopment" so the test runs should always be green.
  8. Use of tags to run only certain tests depending on the deploy market (i.e. some tests have the same tests/results in all markets and there are some Market-depending tests e.g. US vs. Australia) and ignoring tests that aren't applicable.
kimb

Does anything in there seem like a good topic?

tooky

*Thread Reply:* Although I don’t know if SpecFlow supports that yet?

brasmusson
2017-12-09 05:08:26

*Thread Reply:* SpecFlow probably does not. Cucumber-Ruby, Cucumber-JS and Cucumber-JVM have recently started to use "the event model" as interface for formatters and other utilities.

brasmusson
2017-12-09 05:11:40

*Thread Reply:* As I have seen questions and feature requests along the line of "how to access the name of the feature in a Before/After hook - we what to use it for logging/reporting", I'm keen on endorsing the use of event for things like that. Hooks are (IMHO) intended for setup/teardown to be able to execute the testcase/scenario successfully.

Hello @everyone! On Saturday 21st of April we'll be running a Cucumber Open Source day in London. If you're in town for Cukenfest, or if you happen to live nearby, you're welcome to attend.

We'll also set up a video link so people can attend remotely.

The purpose of the day is to do some hacking, and to align the various initiatives that are happening. The ecosystem is so big now that everybody doesn't know what everyone is working on.

I'll publish a blog post later today with logistics, and a rough agenda. If you plan to attend (in person or remotely), let me know what you'd like to work on and/or talk about, and I'll add it to the blog post.

Looking forward to this!

🥒 Michael Stelly

brasmusson
2018-04-20 12:10:45

Presenting? I do not know ... one thing that comes to mind is the step hook feature for Cucumber-JVM, which deviates from the Cucumber-Ruby implementation in three aspects:

  • also before step hooks (for symmetry)
  • execute the test steps for the step hooks also when the test step for the gherkin step fails (but skip test steps for step hooks for subsequent test steps for gherkin steps)
  • add test steps for hooks also in dry run mode (so that the event stream contain events for all test steps that would have been executed if not in dry run mode) But since @mpkorstanje have been as much involved in this feature as I, maybe he could handle the presentation.

Dermot Canniffe
2018-11-28 08:19:25

2 points highlighted by the Hiptest State of BDD survey were;

  1. The percentage of respondants unaware of Living Documentation doubled from 2017 to 2018
  2. BDD is growing at a very fast rate.

Point 1 is well worth discussing, but a theme for the event might be "How do we scale?"

Dermot Canniffe
2018-11-28 08:20:17

This touches on a variety of levels;

Dermot Canniffe
2018-11-28 08:21:29

How do teams scale their BDD practice from scratch to full implementation? How do enterprises scale their BDD practice from one team to many? How do we, as BDD practitioners and proponents, scale our community of practice?

Something that might be useful to start if it’s not already been going is something like “Cucumber Ecosystem Report”… something along the lines of https://snyk.io/blog/jvm-ecosystem-report-2018

Questions like; What % of testing is BBD What editor do you use? How do you execute your BBD? What language do you use? Size of Company Number of people writing/maintaining Feature Files Number of people writing/maintaining Glue/Steps How often are they executed? Source Control used? git? other? Number of Projects using Cucumber Are you Agile/Waterfall/Other

Snyk
JVM Ecosystem Report 2018 | Snyk
Welcome to the largest survey ever of Java developers. The data presented in the following report was taken from more than 10,200 questionnaires, covering JDK vendors, versions, IDEs, build tools, CI servers, Java EE versions, web frameworks, JVM languages, binary repositories, source code repositories, source code management and much more!
Original URL: https://snyk.io/blog/jvm-ecosystem-report-2018

Emily Bache
2020-06-04 02:43:11

For my session 'hands-on approval testing' you will need to connect to my VNC server to take part. For that you'll need a VNC client like 'realvnc' (https://www.realvnc.com/en/). Then you connect to it by opening a ssh tunnel. Do do that you write something like this in a command prompt:

ssh -L 5901:localhost:5901 -i .ssh/texttest3.pem ec2-user@13.48.137.231

For that to work you will need the key file, 'texttest3.pem', send me a slack DM and I'll share it with you.

When you've got the ssh tunnel open, use the VNC client to connect to 'localhost:1' When it prompts you for a password, write 'texttest2'.

realvnc.com
RealVNC® - Remote access software for desktop and mobile | RealVNC
The original and best for remote access across desktop and mobile. VNC® software enables you to remotely access and securely control your desktop or mobile device. Your computer whenever and wherever you need it.
Original URL: https://www.realvnc.com/en/

Jo Laing
2023-02-16 05:38:38

Hey all,

I wanted to inform you that the team and I have made the difficult decision to alter the format and design of the CukenFest event. As a result, we will not be running an in-person event this year. We have contacted speakers and ticket holders directly by email today.

I appreciate this might be a disappointment to you, but on the flip side, we’ve reimagined how best to bring regular value to the Cucumber and wider BDD communities. The new concept we’ve created is called “CukenSeason”, a free series of fortnightly online sessions. We believe this format will better serve our community and allow for more thought leaders to participate and share their knowledge and experience.

  1. We still want to showcase the talks and speakers already scheduled to attend the in-person event
  2. We are working to refund all registered CukenFest ticket holders via original method of payment. (We need to work through the refunding process so a little patience is much appreciated.)
  3. For our community guests - let's talk about this at next weeks weekly meeting. Feel free to DM me any information regarding any travel or accommodation costs you will require reimbursement for. Details of CukenSeason will follow soon :dancing_pickle:
😢 Benjamin Bischoff, mlvandijk, gaspar, Lisa Crispin, Blaise Pabon
😭 ciaranmcnulty, Blaise Pabon
👍 Dermot Canniffe
